06:13.506 --> 06:18.378
New York City turned out today
to celebrate the U.S. women's
soccer team and their World

06:18.378 --> 06:24.484
Cup victory. Throngs lined
streets in Lower Manhattan for a
ticker tape parade. It was

06:24.484 --> 06:30.724
a first for a women's sport
team, and fans held signs and
chanted "USA." The Americans

06:30.724 --> 06:36.730
beat Japan last weekend for a
record Third World Cup
championship.

06:36.730 --> 06:42.969
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
an Iran nuclear deal delayed;
Greece's latest offer to win

06:42.969 --> 06:49.843
a European bailout; violence,
crime and incarceration rates
for undocumented immigrants in
the U.S.;

06:49.843 --> 06:55.915
David Brooks and E.J. Dionne on
the week's news; Serena Williams
eyes her second grand

06:55.915 --> 07:10.830
slam; and a new look at a
British rock star whose fame and
addiction spelled her demise.

07:10.830 --> 07:15.869
The world's major powers will
continue to negotiate with Iran
throughout the weekend,

07:15.869 --> 07:19.939
aiming to clinch an agreement
that would curb that country's
nuclear program. A number

07:19.939 --> 07:23.576
of self-imposed deadlines
have come and gone.

07:23.576 --> 07:28.248
For an update on where things
stand, we turn to Michael Gordon
of The New York Times,who

07:28.248 --> 07:31.384
has been covering the talks in
Vienna. I spoke with him a
short while ago.

07:31.384 --> 07:34.621
Michael, welcome.

07:34.621 --> 07:39.159
It's late Friday night there,
another delay. Where do things
stand?

07:39.159 --> 07:40.627
MICHAEL GORDON, Diplomatic
Correspondent, The New York
Times: Well, I do have the

07:40.627 --> 07:44.064
sense that they're beginning to
close in on the final accord.
This is going to be the

07:44.064 --> 07:49.469
third weekend that we're here in
Vienna, and I'm positive that
Secretary of State John

07:49.469 --> 07:55.041
Kerry has never been in one
place as long as he's been here
as the secretary of state.

07:55.041 --> 07:57.711
But there is a sense of
progress, and we're waiting to
see if this thing comes together

07:57.711 --> 07:59.913
in the next day or two.

07:59.913 --> 08:04.250
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is it clear what
they have made progress on and
where the hangups are

08:04.250 --> 08:05.919
still?

08:05.919 --> 08:10.523
MICHAEL GORDON: Well, I think
they have made a lot of progress
in defining the nuclear

08:10.523 --> 08:13.426
provisions of the accord.

08:13.426 --> 08:18.598
Certainly, we already know that
they have decided on the number
of centrifuges Iran

08:18.598 --> 08:22.535
will be allowed to have. I
think they have made progress on
what research and development

08:22.535 --> 08:26.506
will be allowed on new types of
centrifuges. I think there have
been some very delicate

08:26.506 --> 08:31.311
issues to work out on -- in
terms of sanctions and the
timing of sanctions relief.

08:31.311 --> 08:35.215
And there was a new one that
cropped up this week. Actually,
it was an old one that
reemerged,

08:35.215 --> 08:38.418
and that's whether to lift the
arms embargo on Iran. And
that's been a very contentious

08:38.418 --> 08:40.420
issue this past week.

08:40.420 --> 08:44.991
JUDY WOODRUFF: So why is that
coming up at the last minute?

08:44.991 --> 08:48.795
MICHAEL GORDON: Well, it's
something that Americans really
thought they had resolved

08:48.795 --> 08:56.836
or at least finessed in Lausanne
in April, and previous Security
Council resolutions

08:56.836 --> 09:01.007
at the United Nations banned the
import or export of conventional
arms and missile technology

09:01.007 --> 09:03.843
to Iran.

09:03.843 --> 09:08.782
And the Iranians had wanted this
off, but that's really a
nonstarter in the American

09:08.782 --> 09:14.254
political system. I mean, the
idea that you're going to give
Iran billions of dollars

09:14.254 --> 09:21.060
in sanctions relief, so that
they can go buy conventional
arms that increases their
military

09:21.060 --> 09:25.365
power in the region is just not
going to fly in the American
Congress or even among President

09:25.365 --> 09:29.936
Obama's Democratic
allies in the Congress.

09:29.936 --> 09:33.907
And the Americans thought they
had that resolved, but it came
back this week. And the
Iranians

09:33.907 --> 09:36.810
had some support really from the
Russians and the Chinese, both
of whom want to sell

09:36.810 --> 09:38.445
them arms.

09:38.445 --> 09:41.614
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you
see that getting resolved?

09:41.614 --> 09:46.986
MICHAEL GORDON: Well, I really
don't think this is one that the
United States can -- will

09:46.986 --> 09:52.992
give in on, and I think probably
the best resolution would be if
both sides come to

09:52.992 --> 09:55.995
the conclusion that there is a
lot more at stake in this
agreement.

09:55.995 --> 09:59.098
This is probably the most
important arms agreement

09:59.098 --> 10:04.070
in several decades, with all
sorts of ramifications for
U.S.-Iranian relation, for the
region.

10:04.070 --> 10:07.774
And I think, in the end, both
sides are going to come to the
conclusion that that's

10:07.774 --> 10:13.813
too important to risk for the
lifting of the arms embargo. I
don't think it will be lifted.

10:13.813 --> 10:18.251
I think it will remain a
feature of a U.N. resolution and
I think the Iranians the
Russians

10:18.251 --> 10:23.122
just won't like it and maybe
they will sort of agree to
disagree. That would be my best

10:23.122 --> 10:25.925
guess as to how this comes out.

10:25.925 --> 10:30.630
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Michael, you
mentioned some disagreement or
difference of opinion

10:30.630 --> 10:38.338
among the U.S. and its
negotiating partners. Is that a
serious? Is that turning out

10:38.338 --> 10:44.444
to be something serious or what?
How do you see the group sitting
across the table

10:44.444 --> 10:46.913
from Iran holding together?

10:46.913 --> 10:51.017
MICHAEL GORDON: Well, the
United States, and particularly
Secretary Kerry, have really

10:51.017 --> 10:56.222
been in the lead for the last
six months, if not longer, and
the other five countries

10:56.222 --> 11:01.160
involved in the talks with Iran
show up at critical junctures.

11:01.160 --> 11:05.665
And the United States has often
said that the Russians have been
very cooperative in

11:05.665 --> 11:10.003
these talks, that this has been
one area of U.S.-Russian
relations where things have gone

11:10.003 --> 11:16.276
well, unlike Ukraine or
Syria or arms control.

11:16.276 --> 11:20.246
But I think the Russians have
been a bit difficult over this
past week because of their
interest

11:20.246 --> 11:25.752
in getting the arms embargo
lifted for their own, really,
financial reasons. But I think,

11:25.752 --> 11:29.822
in the end, if Iran can live
with the agreement, the Russians
and Chinese will go along, and

11:29.822 --> 11:33.092
I don't really see it
as a show-stopper.

11:33.092 --> 11:37.997
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael Gordon
with The New York Times spending
one more weekend in Vienna,

11:37.997 --> 11:39.999
we thank you.

11:39.999 --> 11:46.806
MICHAEL GORDON: Thank you.

11:46.806 --> 11:53.446
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: the drama
in Greece heading toward a
climax at a Sunday summit

11:53.446 --> 11:56.449
of European leaders.

11:56.449 --> 12:02.121
The Greek prime minister has now
offered concessions to
creditors, ranging from a higher
sales

12:02.121 --> 12:06.759
tax, the so-called VAT -- VAT --
to pension changes. The goal?
A new bailout worth

12:06.759 --> 12:10.129
nearly $60 billion.

12:10.129 --> 12:13.399
Jonathan Rugman of Independent
Television News reports.

12:13.399 --> 12:17.503
JONATHAN RUGMAN: Climbing the
steps of Greece's Parliament
today, the members of a
government

12:17.503 --> 12:23.242
forced into a last -minute climb
down. Days ago, they were
railing against Greece's
creditors.

12:23.242 --> 12:28.147
Today, they were talking up the
chances of a new deal with them
this weekend.

12:28.147 --> 12:32.719
OLGA GEROVASILI, Greek
Parliament Member (through
translator): I am certain we
will reach

12:32.719 --> 12:35.989
an agreement. There was never
any doubt. The battle was
lengthy and long and will

12:35.989 --> 12:39.492
reach its conclusion by taking
the steps you already know
about.

12:39.492 --> 12:44.764
JONATHAN RUGMAN: And greeted
like a conquering hero, Alexis
Tsipras, the prime minister,

12:44.764 --> 12:49.602
who is now pushing through
Parliament the kind of austerity
61 percent of Greek voters

12:49.602 --> 12:55.742
rejected last weekend, because
money or lack of it talks.

12:55.742 --> 13:01.080
These banks could be bankrupt by
Monday, and so the government,
it seems, has blinked.

13:01.080 --> 13:07.820
Greece's proposals are on time
and to the kind of budget a wary
Eurozone might accept,

13:07.820 --> 13:14.093
giving into more austerity, with
a standard VAT rate at 23
percent beginning in October,

13:14.093 --> 13:20.800
reducing the 30 percent VAT tax
break applied to tourism-rich
Greek islands, corporation

13:20.800 --> 13:26.339
tax rising from 26 percent to 28
percent, as Greece's creditors
demanded, and raising

13:26.339 --> 13:31.811
the standard retirement age to
67 over the next seven years.

13:31.811 --> 13:38.685
But what is Mr. Tsipras hoping
to win in return? Well, 53.5
billion euros in loans over
three

13:38.685 --> 13:45.591
years and, crucially,
restructuring the repayment of
Greece's vast debt, though the
13 billion

13:45.591 --> 13:50.697
euros in tax rises and spending
cuts is at least four billion
euros more than the package

13:50.697 --> 13:54.400
Greeks on Sunday voted against.

13:54.400 --> 14:00.239
A new and lasting deal with
Greece will depend on the Greeks
actually doing what they say

14:00.239 --> 14:06.145
they will and not buckling under
the weight of more austerity.
And Germany will need

14:06.145 --> 14:11.551
to agree on some form of debt
relief which doesn't leave
German taxpayers feeling
shortchanged.

14:11.551 --> 14:16.889
But whatever the outcome of
this weekend's talks, Greece is
heading for years of economic

14:16.889 --> 14:23.062
hardship and the debate over its
Eurozone membership is very
unlikely to stop.

14:23.062 --> 14:29.168
No wonder there are protests in
Athens tonight by some of those
who said no and meant it,

14:29.168 --> 14:32.772
though the French, who helped
draw up this plan, are perhaps
prematurely hailing it as

14:32.772 --> 14:34.941
a breakthrough.

14:34.941 --> 14:39.078
FRANCOIS HOLLANDE, French
President (through translator):
Since the program they are

14:39.078 --> 14:43.750
presenting is serious and
credible, and because they won't
submit it to the Parliament,
that

14:43.750 --> 14:49.288
shows strength, commitment and
indeed courage. So, the
discussions now need to start,
resume,

14:49.288 --> 14:52.258
with the will to conclude.

14:52.258 --> 14:57.497
JONATHAN RUGMAN: Tonight,
Greece's Parliament is set to
back its government, and
Eurozone

14:57.497 --> 15:03.503
finance ministers may do the
same tomorrow. And if they do,
Greece's banks could be

15:03.503 --> 15:09.642
refinanced and reopen on Monday,
though today's climb-down could
leave the pensioners feeling

15:09.642 --> 15:15.214
worse off than before.

15:15.214 --> 15:25.558
JUDY WOODRUFF: We turn now to
immigration. The complex issue
has remained frozen in

15:25.558 --> 15:29.662
Washington for years, but is
quickly heating up outside the
capital.

15:29.662 --> 15:33.099
Our William Brangham
unravels the debate.

15:33.099 --> 15:37.136
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The firestorm
started when in his announcement
that he was running

15:37.136 --> 15:40.840
for president, Donald Trump
turned to the topic of
immigration.

15:40.840 --> 15:44.277
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate: When Mexico sends
its people, they're not

15:44.277 --> 15:50.016
sending their best. They're not
sending you. They're not
sending you. They're

15:50.016 --> 15:55.188
sending people that have lots of
problems. And they're bringing
those problems with

15:55.188 --> 16:00.593
us. They're bringing drugs.
They're bringing crime. They're
rapists. And some, I assume,

16:00.593 --> 16:03.162
are good people.

16:03.162 --> 16:07.433
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In the weeks
following, major businesses
connected to Trump backed

16:07.433 --> 16:13.072
away from partnerships and
projects with him. They
included NBC, Univision, Macy's,
ESPN,

16:13.072 --> 16:15.141
and the Professional
Golf Association.

16:15.141 --> 16:20.713
For his part, Trump stood by his
comments. But then a tragedy in
San Francisco added

16:20.713 --> 16:26.319
fuel to the fire; 32-year-old
Kathryn Steinle was shot and
killed at the end of last month.

16:26.319 --> 16:30.122
Undocumented immigrant Juan
Lopez-Sanchez confessed to a
reporter that he shot her,

16:30.122 --> 16:33.226
but said it was an accident.

16:33.226 --> 16:37.196
All this has just inflamed the
debate about immigration in the
U.S., whether immigrants

16:37.196 --> 16:41.334
are a positive force in the
country or whether they should
be feared. There are currently

16:41.334 --> 16:44.470
more than 41 million immigrants
in America. Over 11 million are
estimated to be here

16:44.470 --> 16:47.840
illegally.

16:47.840 --> 16:51.444
To help us understand what we
know about the nation's
immigrants, legal and illegal,
I'm

16:51.444 --> 16:54.580
joined by three people who
have studied the research.

16:54.580 --> 16:59.619
Marielena Hincapie is the
executive director of the
National Immigration Law Center,
an

16:59.619 --> 17:04.190
immigration rights group. Marc
Rosenblum is from the
nonpartisan Migration Policy
Institute.

17:04.190 --> 17:06.792
And Jessica Vaughan is with the
Center for Immigration Studies,
which advocates for tougher

17:06.792 --> 17:08.361
border security.

17:08.361 --> 17:09.962
Welcome to all three of you.

17:09.962 --> 17:11.764
MARC ROSENBLUM, Migration
Policy Institute: Thank you.

17:11.764 --> 17:15.735
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Marc
Rosenblum, why don't I start
with you first?

17:15.735 --> 17:19.438
Donald Trump is saying that
immigrants come to the country
and they commit a
disproportionate

17:19.438 --> 17:23.309
amount of crime. You have
looked at this data quite a bit.
Is he right?

17:23.309 --> 17:26.679
MARC ROSENBLUM: You know, it's
a very persistent stereotype,
but there's a lot of research

17:26.679 --> 17:31.017
on it, looking at prison
populations and looking at city
crime rates.

17:31.017 --> 17:37.290
And what it shows is that
immigrants are
disproportionately unlikely to
be in prison. The prison

17:37.290 --> 17:40.860
doesn't have a lot of immigrants
in it. And when you look at
crime rates and correlate

17:40.860 --> 17:43.429
them with immigration
populations, immigrants are --
cities with lots of immigrants
don't

17:43.429 --> 17:45.598
have lots of crime.

17:45.598 --> 17:48.668
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Sarah (sic)
Vaughan, I know you have looked
at this data as well.

17:48.668 --> 17:51.237
What do you make
of this analysis?

17:51.237 --> 17:53.472
JESSICA VAUGHAN, Center for
Immigration Studies: Well, no,
we have looked at it very
deeply.

